There are three stages of complexity: systems that are truly basic, 
systems whose components are mostly understandable, and
systems with incomprehensible components.
People recognize the third type as “magic”, but often mistake the second for “simple.” https://t.co/Y6L0aigG6W

@Devon_Eriksen_ Most people who’ve done organizational design, even on a small scale, get this: humans aren’t ants, and their self-interest (rational and otherwise) will always alter the effects of the rules you try to implement.
@Devon_Eriksen_ Sometimes, third-stage systems are less complex than second-stage systems, but their components are too arcane for most humans to ever mistakenly think that they are simple systems.

Then there are the other end of second-stage systems: ones so complex that no human can really understand them, but people do.  This is, I think, what resonated with people in @Devon_Eriksen_’s thread yesterday: societies are emergent systems, too complex for human design.

In writing today's newsletter (There are no micro-aggressions), I drew a lot from two rabbinical scholars: @RabbiWolpe, who is quoted in the prompt, and from Hillel, as he stood on 1 foot. 1/ https://t.co/ckFkuZNmSB

Say then that it's a micro-exclusion. A lack of micro-inclusion. But if it's truly an aggression, there is nothing "micro" about it ... and if it's truly micro, then it isn't an aggression. It's just an opportunity to be better. 7/

But calling it a micro-aggression is a way to escalate a small thing into a big thing. Which may feel right in the moment to the person who felt harm ... but it sows more ill will in the world as a result. 8/FIN

How does that become "There are no micro-aggressions"? Calling an action a micro-aggression is an assumption of ill intent. It might or might not be harmful, but calling it an aggression is a judgement, and the listener finds that hateful. 6/
